  <li class="arxiv-result">
    <div class="is-marginless">
      <p class="list-title is-inline-block"><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0003224">arXiv:math/0003224</a>
        <span>&nbsp;[<a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0003224">pdf</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/ps/math/0003224">ps</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/format/math/0003224">other</a>]&nbsp;</span>
      </p>
      <div class="tags is-inline-block">
        <span class="tag is-small is-link tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Rings and Algebras">math.RA</span>
        </div>
      
    </div>
    
    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Rank Equalities Related to Generalized Inverses of Matrices and Their Applications
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Tian%2C+Y">Yongge Tian</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/0003224v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        This paper is divided into two parts. In the first part, we develop a general method for expressing ranks of matrix expressions that involve Moore-Penrose inverses, group inverses, Drazin inverses, as well as weighted Moore-Penrose inverses of matrices. Through this method we establish a variety of valuable rank equalities related to generalized inverses of matrices mentioned above. Using them,&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('math/0003224v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('math/0003224v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/0003224v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
          This paper is divided into two parts. In the first part, we develop a general method for expressing ranks of matrix expressions that involve Moore-Penrose inverses, group inverses, Drazin inverses, as well as weighted Moore-Penrose inverses of matrices. Through this method we establish a variety of valuable rank equalities related to generalized inverses of matrices mentioned above. Using them, we characterize many matrix equalities in the theory of generalized inverses of matrices and their applications. In the second part, we consider maximal and minimal possible ranks of matrix expressions that involve variant matrices, the fundamental work is concerning extreme ranks of the two linear matrix expressions $A - BXC$ and $A - B_1X_1C_1 - B_2X_2C_2$. As applications, we present a wide range of their consequences and applications in matrix theory.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('math/0003224v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('math/0003224v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 30 March, 2000; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2000.
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="comments is-size-7">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Comments:</span>
      <span class="has-text-grey-dark mathjax">245 pages, LaTex</span>
    </p>
    

    
      <p class="comments is-size-7">
        
          <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Report number:</span>
          formerly <span class="search-hit mathjax">math.LA</span>/0003224
        

        
          <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">MSC Class:</span>
          15A03;15A09;15A24
        

        
      </p>
    

    
  </li>

  <li class="arxiv-result">
    <div class="is-marginless">
      <p class="list-title is-inline-block"><a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/math/0003167">arXiv:math/0003167</a>
        <span>&nbsp;[<a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/math/0003167">pdf</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/ps/math/0003167">ps</a>, <a href="https://arxiv.org/format/math/0003167">other</a>]&nbsp;</span>
      </p>
      <div class="tags is-inline-block">
        <span class="tag is-small is-link tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Rings and Algebras">math.RA</span>
        
          
            <span class="tag is-small is-grey tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Mathematical Physics">math-ph</span>
          
            <span class="tag is-small is-grey tooltip is-tooltip-top" data-tooltip="Representation Theory">math.RT</span>
          
        </div>
      
    </div>
    
    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Universal Similarity Factorization Equalities over Complex Clifford Algebras
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Tian%2C+Y">Yongge Tian</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/0003167v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        A set of valuable universal similarity factorization equalities are established over complex Clifford algebras $\Cn.$ Through them matrix representations of complex Clifford algebras $\Cn$ can directly be derived, and their properties can easily be determined.
        
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/0003167v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
          A set of valuable universal similarity factorization equalities are established over complex Clifford algebras $\Cn.$ Through them matrix representations of complex Clifford algebras $\Cn$ can directly be derived, and their properties can easily be determined.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('math/0003167v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('math/0003167v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 26 March, 2000; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2000.
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="comments is-size-7">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Comments:</span>
      <span class="has-text-grey-dark mathjax">12 pages, LaTex, paper presented at the 5th International Conference on Clifford Algebras and their Applications in Mathematical Physics, Ixtapa, Mexico, June 27 - July 4, 1999</span>
    </p>
    

    
      <p class="comments is-size-7">
        
          <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Report number:</span>
          formerly <span class="search-hit mathjax">math.LA</span>/0003167
        

        
          <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">MSC Class:</span>
          15A33; 15A66
        

        
      </p>
    

    
