    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        s-convexity, model sets and their relation
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Mas%C3%A1kov%C3%A1%2C+Z">Zuzana Masáková</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Patera%2C+J">Jiří Patera</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Pelantov%C3%A1%2C+E">Edita Pelantová</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/9907054v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        The relation of s-convexity and sets modeling physical quasicrystals is explained for quasicrystals related to quadratic unitary Pisot numbers. We show that 1-dimensional model sets may be characterized by s-convexity for finite set of parameters s. It is shown that the three Pisot numbers $\frac12(1+\sqrt5)$, $1+\sqrt2$, and $2+\sqrt3$ related to experimentally observed non-crystallographic sym&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('math/9907054v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('math/9907054v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/9907054v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
          The relation of s-convexity and sets modeling physical quasicrystals is explained for quasicrystals related to quadratic unitary Pisot numbers. We show that 1-dimensional model sets may be characterized by s-convexity for finite set of parameters s. It is shown that the three Pisot numbers $\frac12(1+\sqrt5)$, $1+\sqrt2$, and $2+\sqrt3$ related to experimentally observed non-crystallographic symmetries are exceptional with respect to s-convexity.
