    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Partial norms and the convergence of general products of matrices
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Neumann%2C+M">Michael Neumann</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Schneider%2C+H">Hans Schneider</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/9802108v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        Motivated by the theory of inhomogeneous Markov chains, we determine a sufficient condition for the convergence to 0 of a general product formed from a sequence of real or complex matrices. When the matrices have a common invariant subspace $H$, we give a sufficient condition for the convergence to 0 on $H$ of a general product. Our result is applied to obtain a condition for the weak ergodicity&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('math/9802108v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('math/9802108v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="math/9802108v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
          Motivated by the theory of inhomogeneous Markov chains, we determine a sufficient condition for the convergence to 0 of a general product formed from a sequence of real or complex matrices. When the matrices have a common invariant subspace $H$, we give a sufficient condition for the convergence to 0 on $H$ of a general product. Our result is applied to obtain a condition for the weak ergodicity of an inhomogeneous Markov chain. We compare various types of contractions which may be defined for a single matrix, such as paracontraction, $l$--contraction, and $H$--contraction, where $H$ is an invariant subspace of the matrix.
